Date: 0/0/1949
Source: Shepherd's Dogs, The
Author: HARTLEY
Vol / Page: 71
Edition:
Quote: Over-running the head. This is not as serious as short heading providing the dog is quickly manoeuvred into the correct position.
Notes:

Date: 5/7/1951
Source: NZ Farmer
Author:
Vol / Page: 32
Edition:
Quote: Matheson's Snow showed great speed but was slightly wide at the top of his cast, and then he slightly overran his head.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1964
Source: Practical Guide to Handling Dogs and Stock
Author: MILLS ET AL
Vol / Page: 36
Edition:
Quote: If Boy stops to the right of this line he is said to have 'short-headed.' On the other hand if he goes past the line he has 'overrun his head.' If the sheep is facing right and he continues on to the straight-line position he has also overrun his head. From a distance it is often difficult to be sure if a dog has stopped on the point of balance, or overrun his head or has short-headed.
Notes:
